# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dust-explosion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] On 7 February 2008, fourteen people were killed and thirty-six injured during a dust explosion at a refinery owned by Imperial Sugar in Port Wentworth, Georgia, United States.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Dust explosions had been an issue of concern among U.S. authorities since three fatal accidents in 2003, with efforts made to improve safety and reduce the risk of reoccurrence.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Port Wentworth refinery was large and old, featuring outdated construction methods, factors which are believed to have contributed to the fire's severity.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The origin of the explosion was narrowed down to the center of the factory, in a basement located beneath storage silos.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Large accumulations of sugar dust due to poor housekeeping became airborne from the initial shock waves, leading to a series of massive secondary explosions spreading throughout the factory.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Investigations conducted by the Department of Justice ruled out deliberate criminal activity in 2013.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] As a result of the industrial disaster, new safety legislation was proposed.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Port Wentworth's economy declined because the factory had ceased operating.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial intended to rebuild it and return to production by the end of 2008, with replacement buildings to be completed by summer the following year.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Victims filed up to 44 lawsuits for damages against Imperial and/or the company hired to clean up the site.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial said that the explosion was the main reason for a major loss in the first quarter of 2008.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Chemical Safety Board (CSB) released its report on the incident in September 2009, saying that the explosion had been "entirely preventable".
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Investigations by Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF) reached similar conclusions.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial Sugar's refinery in Port Wentworth, Georgia, was a four-story structure on the bank of the Savannah River.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial, based in Sugar Land, Texas, had bought the refinery and its brand name in 1997 from a previous local owner.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Known since construction as the Dixie Crystal refinery, it was the main employer in Port Wentworth, a town of 3,500, prior to the disaster.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Port Wentworth refinery was constructed in 1916 by 400 people who were moved from Louisiana specifically for this purpose, and opened the following year.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial bought the refinery together with Savannah Foods to form part of a national supply and distribution network to meet demand from businesses such as Piggly Wiggly, General Mills and Wal-Mart.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] This network was the second largest in the United States.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Workers described the factory as antiquated, with much of the machinery dating back more than twenty-eight years.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The site had continued operating because it had good access to rail and shipping links for transport.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] 90% of the raw sugar supplied to the facility came from overseas in that year, and Imperial expected the "vast majority" to come in from abroad in the year of the explosion as well.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In the time leading up to the explosion, Imperial had run into financial difficulties.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In the fiscal year ending September 30, 2007, sales had fallen eight percent while the company's profits and stock price had fallen by half.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The last two annual reports by Imperial before the explosion said that any damage to the facility at Port Wentworth would "have a material effect on the company's business, financial condition, results of operations and cash flows".
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Meanwhile, in 2004 the CSB conducted a study into the risks presented by dust explosions after three fatal accidents in the year before.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The West Pharmaceutical Services explosion in North Carolina killed six persons, the CTA Acoustics explosion in Kentucky killed seven, and the Hayes Lemmerz explosion in Indiana killed one, prompting the report.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The CSB found that between 1980 and 2005, there had been 281 explosions involving combustible dust, resulting in 119 deaths and 718 injuries.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The agency made a number of recommendations to the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), which had been partly implemented by 2008.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The CSB continued to be concerned about the potential for further fatal accidents up until the explosion at the Imperial refinery in Port Wentworth.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The explosion occurred at 7 p.m. local time in what was initially believed to be a room where sugar was bagged by workers.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Witnesses from across the Savannah River in South Carolina reported seeing flames shoot up several stories high.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] There were 112 employees on-site at the time.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The explosion occurred in the center of the refinery, where bagging and storage facilities were fed sugar by a network of elevators and conveyor belts.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Many of the buildings at this location were six to eight stories high with narrow gaps in between.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Ambulances responded to the scene from across twelve counties, and firefighters from three.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The United States Coast Guard closed off the river in the area, and a firefighting tugboat was used to douse the fire from the river.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A helicopter was used to search the river for anyone who may have been thrown into it by the blast.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Off-duty employees were brought in to assist with search and rescue operations, as emergency services personnel were unfamiliar with the plant's layout.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Red Cross worker Joyce Baker, who was among the first to arrive at the scene, reported that it was like "walking into hell", with some of the men she treated having "no skin at all", while others had skin "just dripping off them".
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Georgia Emergency Management Agency (GEMHSA) alerted local hospitals to prepare for up to 100 casualties.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A doctor at nearby Memorial Health Hospital described patients arriving at an emergency triage as varying in condition from suffering minor burns to their hands to having received 80-90 percent burns, with many in critical condition, and one with 95 percent burns.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Many victims were placed in artificial comas because they were on life support systems.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Eight were transported by helicopter to the specialized Joseph M.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Still Burn Center in Augusta, about an hour away.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Five of those injured later died there while receiving treatment.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A church close to the refinery was used as a point for families seeking information on relatives employed at the facility.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] So many people came that police requested that each family send only one representative.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] At the close of the day of the explosion, six people were missing, with no confirmed deaths.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Overnight, several deep-seated fires were uncovered, and firefighting continued the next day.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Most of the three-mile (5 km) stretch of river that had previously been closed was reopened without restriction, although a patrol remained in place to enforce a safety zone.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The river restrictions delayed one outgoing vessel and two incoming ones.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] There was also a minor oil spill originating from equipment at the refinery's unoccupied and rarely used dock.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The explosion seriously weakened the structure of the refinery, leaving it highly unstable.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The packaging area was totally destroyed; twelve percent of the refinery was demolished by the explosion.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Removal of debris began the day after the accident, with assistance from structural engineers.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The six missing persons were all found dead that day, three of them in tunnels running beneath the facility.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It was the first major shutdown of a U.S. sugar refinery since American Sugar Refining Inc.'s Domino Sugar shut down its plant in Chalmette, Louisiana, in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] After seven days, on February 14, 2008, the worst of the fire had been extinguished.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The 100-foot (30 m) sugar storage silos remained alight despite attempts to put the fire out by dousing them with thousands of gallons of water from a helicopter.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Specialist crews and equipment were called in to complete work tackling the smoldering, molten sugar in the silos.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] At this time, seven bodies had been recovered, and an eighth person had died in the hospital.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The location of the explosion was quickly established as a building used to store refined sugar before packaging it and two of three 100-foot (30 m) tall, 18-inch (46 cm) thick reinforced concrete storage silos adjacent to it, as pictured.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] According to Imperial Sugar CEO John Sheptor, the accumulated sugar dust likely acted like gunpowder.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Sheptor, who was in the plant at the time of the explosion, survived only because he was protected by a firewall.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Heavy equipment had to be used to shore up the partially collapsed structure before firefighters could enter it to search for victims.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Within twenty-four hours, the explosive substance was identified as sugar dust.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Federal investigations by OSHA and the CSB were launched, and they interviewed witnesses, checked documentation, and conducted on-scene examination of the plant.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA arrived within two hours and the CSB within forty-eight hours.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Other brief investigations were conducted by state firefighters and police and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms, and Explosives (ATF), but these were ended quickly after confirming there was no evidence of the explosion and fire having been deliberately started.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In a press conference held on February 17, 2008, one of the six members of the CSB team said that the explosion showed the ongoing risk from dust explosions despite their report highlighting the matter in 2004.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Investigators were unable to enter the silos as OSHA ruled them to be too hazardous after the explosion.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] They were only able to access the area after the silos were demolished.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] By the time this took place, four months after the disaster, investigators believed that the explosion started in a basement area beneath the silos, from which sugar was fed up to the packaging building on conveyor belts.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The factory's outdated construction materials and methods are believed to have contributed to the severity of the blaze.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The ceiling was of wooden tongue and groove design.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The creosote used throughout was known as “fat lighter,” because of the fire risk it posed.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Interviews of Imperial employees conducted by OSHA uncovered a lack of training, as forty of the workers reported never receiving training on how to exit the building in an emergency.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Only five employees recalled having a fire drill.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial's refinery in Louisiana was shut down by the company six weeks after the Port Wentworth disaster, over fears a similar explosion would occur there.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It was kept from operating for more than a week.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA fined Imperial $36,000 over safety legislation violations at that plant.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Georgia plant's 371 workers continued to receive payment from Imperial, and 275 were rehired to assist with cleanup and demolition of parts of the refinery that could not be salvaged.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Work began on April 18, 2008, after Imperial's board confirmed their intention to rebuild.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The plan was for the plant to return to sugar refining by the end of 2008.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Demolition of the sugar silos was conducted on June 24, 2008, with a wrecking ball.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A replacement packaging building and new sugar silos were intended to be completed by summer 2009.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] During demolition, 2,800,000 pounds (1,300,000 kg) of fire-hardened sugar were recovered from one silo, and another 500,000 pounds (230,000 kg) from the second silo.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The company hoped to recycle the product for ethanol production.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In the first quarter of 2008, Imperial posted a $15.5 million loss, which they said was primarily due to the explosion.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Port Wentworth suffered an economic depression after the accident, with local businesses losing many customers.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial was purchased in 2012 by the Louis Dreyfus Group.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Within a month of the accident, OSHA, fearing that many employers may be unaware their facilities presented a risk of dust explosions, sent a letter to 30,000 employees to alert them to the danger of a similar explosion occurring.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA also proposed the *Combustible Dust Explosion and Fire Prevention Act of 2008*, a new bill aimed at introducing regulations to reduce the risk of dust explosions.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The bill passed the United States House of Representatives but never passed the United States Senate.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In 2009 OSHA began developing a federal standard for combustible dust.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Congress introduced a bill in 2013 to require OSHA to issue an interim standard based on the voluntary combustible standard set by National Fire Protection Association.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The CSB released its report in September 2009, saying the explosion had been "entirely preventable".
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It noted that the sugar industry had been aware of the risk of dust explosions since 1926.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Specifically, internal company memorandums by managers in 1967 expressed their concern about the potential of explosions from sugar dust.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial Sugar had made construction changes before the explosion, that enabled the accumulation of sugar dust.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It had never practiced evacuation procedures, and the lack of emergency lighting meant that people were confined to dark hallways and tunnels at the time of the explosions.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Victims of the disaster continued to file claims against Imperial Sugar and its construction contractor.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] By September 2010, 44 civil suits had been filed in Chatham County Court in relation to the explosion, and eighteen had been settled.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The state appeals court rejected an effort by defendants' attorneys for a pre-trial appeal in two related cases in an effort to limit damages.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In 2011 Lawrence Manker Jr., an Imperial worker who underwent 70 surgeries for burns covering 85% of his body after the plant explosion, settled his lawsuit with the company for an undisclosed amount.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] He was the last victim to leave a hospital burn unit.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In March 2008, Raquel Islas, a female worker whose arms were burnt, sued Savannah-based company Stokes Contracting, which was a contracted construction company.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In April 2008, the widow of Shelathia Harvey also sued Stokes, as well as Savannah Foods, which operated the refinery along with Imperial.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In August 2008, Malcolm Frazier, who suffered burns over 85% of his body, succumbed to his injuries at the Joseph M.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Still Burn Center, where he had remained since the explosion.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The United States Department of Labor requested that Ed Tarver, U.S.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Attorney for the Southern District of Georgia, pursue criminal prosecution against Imperial and its executives.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA cited Imperial with 124 safety violations, finding that the company acted with "plain indifference to, or intentional disregard for, employee safety and health".
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Tarver said there was not enough evidence of intentional disregard or plain indifference to bring criminal charges against Imperial.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] He also cited a lack of federal criminal laws specifically related to safety in the sugar industry as a reason for his decision.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA fined Imperial $8.8 million in May 2010 after citing the company for 211 violations at the Port Wentworth plant and the plant in Louisiana.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] After settlement negotiations the company agreed to pay $6 million, while admitting no fault.
[src:dust-explosion/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] On February 7, 2009, a monument honoring the people lost in the explosion was dedicated at Legacy Park, on the grounds of the Port Wentworth plant.
[src:dust-explosion/2014-kunshan-explosion] The **2014 Kunshan explosion** (Chinese: 2014年昆山中荣工厂爆炸事故; pinyin: *2014 Nián Kūnshān Zhōngróng Gōngchǎng Bàozhà Shìgù*) was a dust explosion that occurred at Zhongrong Metal Production Company, an automotive parts factory located in Kunshan, Jiangsu, China, on 2 August 2014.
[src:dust-explosion/2014-kunshan-explosion] As of December 30, 2014, the explosion killed 146 workers and injured 114 others.
[src:dust-explosion/2014-kunshan-explosion] A massive explosion occurred at the factory at 7:37 a.m.
[src:dust-explosion/2014-kunshan-explosion] At the time, more than 260 people were present, which was more than the usual number of employees working since overtime wages were doubled during the weekends.
[src:dust-explosion/2014-kunshan-explosion] Forty-four people died at the scene of the explosion, while another 31 died at local hospitals.
[src:dust-explosion/2014-kunshan-explosion] Five hospitals in Kunshan and nearby Suzhou treated over 180 wounded.
[src:dust-explosion/2014-kunshan-explosion] It is believed the explosion may have been caused by flames igniting metal polishing dust.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:dust-explosion/3d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:dust-explosion/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:dust-explosion/after-damp] The proto-Germanic *dampaz* gave rise to many other cognates, including the Old High German *damph*, the Old Norse *dampi*, and the modern German *Dampf*, the last of which still translates as "vapor".
[src:dust-explosion/after-damp] Animal sentinels, such as mice or canaries, are more sensitive to carbon monoxide than humans, so will give a warning to miners.
[src:dust-explosion/after-damp] Canaries were introduced into British collieries in the 1890s by John Scott Haldane, the noted physiologist.
[src:dust-explosion/after-damp] Gas detectors are available now which detect toxic gases such as carbon monoxide at very low levels.
[src:dust-explosion/after-damp] They are widely available to protect domestic premises.
[src:dust-explosion/after-damp] The levels of gas detection depend on the methods used.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:dust-explosion/air-to-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:dust-explosion/air] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:dust-explosion/air] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:dust-explosion/air] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:dust-explosion/air] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:dust-explosion/air] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:dust-explosion/air] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:dust-explosion/air] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:dust-explosion/air] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:dust-explosion/air] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:dust-explosion/air] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:dust-explosion/air] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:dust-explosion/air] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:dust-explosion/air] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:dust-explosion/air] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:dust-explosion/air] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:dust-explosion/air] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:dust-explosion/air] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:dust-explosion/air] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:dust-explosion/air] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:dust-explosion/air] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:dust-explosion/air] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:dust-explosion/air] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:dust-explosion/air] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:dust-explosion/air] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:dust-explosion/air] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:dust-explosion/air] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:dust-explosion/air] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:dust-explosion/air] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:dust-explosion/air] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:dust-explosion/air] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:dust-explosion/air] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:dust-explosion/air] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:dust-explosion/air] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:dust-explosion/air] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:dust-explosion/air] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:dust-explosion/air] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:dust-explosion/air] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:dust-explosion/air] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:dust-explosion/air] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:dust-explosion/air] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:dust-explosion/air] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:dust-explosion/air] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:dust-explosion/air] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:dust-explosion/air] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:dust-explosion/air] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:dust-explosion/air] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:dust-explosion/air] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:dust-explosion/air] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:dust-explosion/air] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:dust-explosion/air] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:dust-explosion/air] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:dust-explosion/air] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:dust-explosion/air] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:dust-explosion/air] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:dust-explosion/air] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:dust-explosion/air] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:dust-explosion/air] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:dust-explosion/air] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:dust-explosion/air] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:dust-explosion/air] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:dust-explosion/air] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:dust-explosion/air] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:dust-explosion/air] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:dust-explosion/air] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:dust-explosion/air] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:dust-explosion/air] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:dust-explosion/air] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:dust-explosion/air] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/air] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:dust-explosion/air] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:dust-explosion/air] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:dust-explosion/air] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] A **dust explosion** is the rapid combustion of fine particles suspended in the air within an enclosed location.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Dust explosions can occur where any dispersed powdered combustible material is present in high-enough concentrations in the atmosphere or other oxidizing gaseous medium, such as pure oxygen.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Dust explosions are a frequent hazard in coal mines, grain elevators and silos, and other industrial environments.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] They are also commonly used by special effects artists, filmmakers, and pyrotechnicians, given their spectacular appearance and ability to be safely contained under certain carefully controlled conditions.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Thermobaric weapons exploit this principle by rapidly saturating an area with an easily combustible material and then igniting it to produce explosive force.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] These weapons are the most powerful non-nuclear explosives in existence.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] If rapid combustion occurs in a confined space, enormous overpressures can build up, causing major structural damage and flying debris.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] The sudden release of energy from a "detonation" can produce a shockwave, either in open air or in a confined space.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] If the spread of flame is at subsonic speed, the phenomenon is sometimes called a "deflagration", although looser usage calls both phenomena "explosions".
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Dust explosions may be classified as being either "primary" or "secondary" in nature.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Primary dust explosions may occur inside process equipment or similar enclosures, and are generally controlled by pressure relief through purpose-built ducting to the external atmosphere.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Secondary dust explosions are the result of dust accumulation inside a building being disturbed and ignited by the primary explosion, resulting in a much more dangerous uncontrolled explosion that can affect the entire structure.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Historically, fatalities from dust explosions have largely been the result of secondary dust explosions.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Many common materials which are known to burn can generate a dust explosion, such as coal dust and sawdust.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] In addition, many otherwise mundane organic materials can also be dispersed into a dangerous dust cloud, such as grain, flour, starch, sugar, powdered milk, cocoa, coffee, and pollen.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Powdered metals (such as aluminum, magnesium, and titanium) can form explosive suspensions in air, if finely divided.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] A gigantic explosion of flour dust destroyed a mill in Minnesota on May 2, 1878, killing 14 workers at the Washburn A Mill and another four in adjacent buildings.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] A similar problem occurs in sawmills and other places dedicated to woodworking.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] For example, in machining operations downstream of the AM build, excess powder liberated from porosities in the support structures can be exposed to sparks from the cutting interface.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Efforts are underway not only to build this knowledgebase within the industry but also to share it with local fire departments, who do periodic fire-safety inspections of businesses in their districts and who can expect to answer alarms at shops or plants where AM is now part of the production mix.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Although not strictly a dust, paper particles emitted during processing – especially rolling, unrolling, calendaring/slitting, and sheet-cutting – are also known to pose an explosion hazard.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Enclosed paper mill areas subject to such dangers commonly maintain very high air humidities to reduce the chance of airborne paper dust explosions.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] In special effects pyrotechnics, lycopodium powder and non-dairy creamer are two common means of producing safe, controlled fire effects.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] To support rapid combustion, the dust must consist of very small particles with a high surface area to volume ratio, thereby making the collective or combined surface area of all the particles very large in comparison to a dust of larger particles.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Dust is defined as powders with particles less than about 500 micrometres in diameter, but finer dust will present a much greater hazard than coarse particles by virtue of the larger total surface area of all the particles.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Below a certain value, the lower explosive limit (LEL), there is insufficient dust to support the combustion at the rate required for an explosion.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] A combustible concentration at or below 25% of the LEL is considered safe.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Similarly, if the fuel to air ratio increases above the upper explosive limit (UEL), there is insufficient oxidant to permit combustion to continue at the necessary rate.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Determining the minimum explosive concentration or maximum explosive concentration of dusts in air is difficult, and consulting different sources can lead to quite different results.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Typical explosive ranges in air are from few dozens grams/m3 for the minimum limit, to few kg/m3 for the maximum limit.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] For example, the LEL for sawdust has been determined to be between 40 and 50 grams/m3.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] It depends on many factors including the type of material used.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Typically, normal atmospheric oxygen can be sufficient to support a dust explosion if the other necessary conditions are also present.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] High-oxygen or pure oxygen environments are considered to be especially hazardous, as are strong oxidizing gases such as chlorine and fluorine.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Also, particulate suspensions of compounds with a high oxidative potential, such as peroxides, chlorates, nitrates, perchlorates, and dichromates, can increase risk of an explosion if combustible materials are also present.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] There are many sources of ignition, and a naked flame need not be the only one: over one half of the dust explosions in Germany in 2005 were from non-flame sources.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] However, it is often difficult to determine the exact source of ignition when investigating after an explosion.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] When a source cannot be found, ignition will often be attributed to static electricity.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Static charges can be generated by external sources, or can be internally generated by friction at the surfaces of particles themselves as they collide or move past one another.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Dust has a very large surface area compared to its mass.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Since burning can only occur at the surface of a solid or liquid, where it can react with oxygen, this causes dust to be much more flammable than bulk materials.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] For example, a 1 kg (2.2 lb) sphere of a combustible material with a density of 1 g/cm3 would be about 12.4 cm (4.9 in) in diameter, and have a surface area of 0.048 m2 (0.52 sq ft).
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] However, if it were broken up into spherical dust particles 50 μm in diametre (about the size of flour particles) it would have a surface area of 120 m2 (1,300 sq ft).
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] This greatly-increased surface area allows the material to burn much faster, and the extremely small mass of each particle allows them to catch on fire with much less energy than the bulk material, as there is no heat loss to conduction within the material.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] When this mixture of fuel and air is ignited, especially in a confined space such as a warehouse or silo, a significant increase in pressure is created, often more than sufficient to demolish the structure.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Even materials that are traditionally thought of as nonflammable (such as aluminium), or slow burning (such as wood), can produce a powerful explosion when finely divided, and can be ignited by even a small spark.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] A dust explosion can cause major damage to structures, equipment, and personnel from violent overpressure or shockwave effects.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Flying objects and debris can cause further damage.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Intense radiant heat from a fireball can ignite the surroundings, or cause severe skin burns in unprotected persons.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] In a tightly enclosed space, the sudden depletion of oxygen can cause asphyxiation.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Where the dust is carbon based (such as in a coal mine), incomplete combustion may cause large amounts of carbon monoxide (the miners' after-damp) to be created.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] This can cause more deaths than the original explosion as well as hindering rescue attempts.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Much research has been carried out in Europe and elsewhere to understand how to control these dangers, but dust explosions still occur.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] The alternatives for making processes and plants safer depend on the industry.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] In the coal mining industry, a methane explosion can initiate a coal dust explosion, which can then engulf an entire mine pit.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] As a precaution, incombustible stone dust may be spread along mine roadways, or stored in trays hanging from the roof, to dilute the coal dust stirred up by a shockwave to the point where it cannot burn.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Mines may also be sprayed with water to inhibit ignition.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Some industries exclude oxygen from dust-raising processes, a precaution known as "inerting".
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Typically this uses nitrogen, carbon dioxide, or argon, which are incombustible gases which can displace oxygen.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] The same method is also used in large storage tanks where flammable vapors can accumulate.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] However, use of oxygen-free gases brings a risk of asphyxiation of the workers.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Workers who need illumination in enclosed spaces where a dust explosion is a high risk often use lamps designed for underwater divers, as they have no risk of producing an open spark due to their sealed waterproof design.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Good housekeeping practices, such as eliminating build-up of combustible dust deposits with a dust collector, also help mitigate the problem.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] Dust clouds are a common source of explosions, causing an estimated 2,000 explosions annually in Europe.
[src:dust-explosion/dust-explosion] The table lists notable incidents worldwide.
